text.tspan: Each genome determines a different attractor landscape in which the states of genes develop towards stable basins of attraction.
Depending on the initial conditions (for example in the posterior or anterior cortex), the states will take a different path through these
attractors (blue or red lines). A small mutational change in the genome (P1) yields similar attractor landscapes, whereas a larger
mutational change (P2) yields very different basins of attraction. It is also therefore probable that the resulting fitness of mutationally close organisms
will be similar. In other words the self-organisational process of the regulatory network gives structure to the fitness landscape which natural selection can take advantage of.
